# ESLint Rules

## Core Rules

- See [Core Concepts](mdc:.cursor/rules/core.mdc) for project setup
- Use Standard.js rules
- Use TypeScript rules
- Use React rules
- Use TypeScript-ESLint recommended and stylistic rules
- Follow Prettier formatting
- Enforce consistent imports and exports sorting
- Enforce consistent file naming (camelCase, kebabCase, or pascalCase)

## TypeScript Rules

- Use type imports with inline style

  ```typescript
  // ✅ Good
  import type { User } from './types';
  import { type Config } from './config';

  // ❌ Bad
  import { User } from './types';
  import { Config } from './config';
  ```

- Use type definitions over interfaces

  ```typescript
  // ✅ Good
  type User = {
    id: string;
    name: string;
  };

  // ❌ Bad
  interface User {
    id: string;
    name: string;
  }
  ```

- Ignore unused variables with underscore prefix

  ```typescript
  // ✅ Good
  function handler(_event: Event) {
    // ...
  }

  // ❌ Bad
  function handler(event: Event) {
    // ...
  }
  ```

## React Rules

- Use JSX Runtime
- Follow React Hooks rules
- Follow accessibility (a11y) guidelines
- Sort JSX props:

  ```tsx
  // ✅ Good
  <Button
    ref={buttonRef}
    className="btn"
    disabled={isLoading}
    type="submit"
    onClick={handleClick}
  >
    Submit
  </Button>

  // ❌ Bad
  <Button
    onClick={handleClick}
    disabled={isLoading}
    className="btn"
    type="submit"
    ref={buttonRef}
  >
    Submit
  </Button>
  ```

## Import Rules

- Sort imports consistently
- No duplicate imports
- Add newline after imports
- Group imports:

  ```typescript
  // 1. React imports
  import { useState } from 'react';

  // 2. External libraries
  import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';
  import { z } from 'zod';

  // 3. Internal absolute imports
  import { type User } from '~/types';

  // 4. Internal relative imports
  import { UserCard } from './UserCard';
  ```

## Special Cases

- Sort keys rule is disabled for:
  - Route files
  - Schema files
